---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import blogsData from '../../data/blogs.json';
import postsData from '../../data/cache/posts.json';

const blogs = blogsData.blogs;
const totalPosts = postsData.posts.length;
---

<Base title="About — The Small Web">
  <header class="site-header">
    <div class="header-inner">
      <a href="/" class="logo">The Small Web</a>
      <nav class="header-nav">
        <a href="/">Home</a>
        <a href="/feed">Feed</a>
        <a href="/archive">Archive</a>
        <a href="/blogs">Blogs</a>
        <a href="/about" class="active">About</a>
        <a href="https://buymeacoffee.com/bebhuvan" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="nav-support">Support</a>
        <button class="theme-toggle" id="theme-toggle">Dark mode</button>
      </nav>
    </div>
  </header>

  <main style="max-width: 700px; margin: 0 auto; padding: 4rem 2rem;">
    <div class="page-header" style="margin-bottom: 3rem;">
      <h1 class="page-title" style="font-size: 3rem;">About</h1>
    </div>

    <div class="content">
      <p>This is a collection of indie blogs and publications I've come across over time. The idea is simple: instead of doomscrolling on Twitter, you could doomscroll here and actually find interesting links—rabbit holes worth going down.</p>

      <p>The only filter I have is whether I've actually read something from each writer. That's it. I'm not curating based on whether I agree or disagree with them—just whether I've found their work interesting enough to keep reading. These are some really smart people, and I think more people should read them.</p>

      <p>I've also included a few aggregators I like—<a href="https://abnormalreturns.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Abnormal Returns</a>, <a href="https://aldaily.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Arts & Letters Daily</a>, and others. They're doing similar work, surfacing good writing from across the web.</p>

      <h2>How it works</h2>

      <p>RSS feeds are fetched automatically twice a day. Posts appear chronologically—no algorithms deciding what you should see. No tracking, no ads.</p>

      <div class="stats">
        <div class="stat">
          <div class="stat-value">{blogs.length}</div>
          <div class="stat-label">blogs</div>
        </div>
        <div class="stat">
          <div class="stat-value">{totalPosts}</div>
          <div class="stat-label">posts</div>
        </div>
        <div class="stat">
          <div class="stat-value">0</div>
          <div class="stat-label">ads</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p><a href="/blogs" style="color: var(--accent);">See all {blogs.length} blogs →</a></p>

      <h2>About the site</h2>

      <p>I have absolutely no technical knowledge. This entire site was built with <a href="https://claude.ai" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Claude</a>—I just described what I wanted, and we figured it out together. If AI can help someone with zero coding skills build something useful, that feels like a good use of the technology.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="contact">
      <h3>Know a good blog?</h3>
      <p>If you read someone interesting who isn't here, let me know.</p>
      <a href="mailto:hello@smallweb.blog" class="contact-btn">
        Send a suggestion
      </a>
    </div>

    <div class="support">
      <p>If you find this useful, you can buy me a coffee.</p>
      <a href="https://buymeacoffee.com/bebhuvan" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="coffee-btn">
